[2] Gambia - cVDPV2
Date: Fri 20 Aug 2021
Source: EpiCore member [edited]
https://epicore.org


We received a reply from an EpiCore member in response to an RFI (request for information). The reply confirmed that as of yesterday (20 Aug 2021) there had been 2 positive environmental samples identified -- 1 in Banjul and 1 in Kotu that were positive for cVDPV2. But as of yesterday (20 Aug 2021) there were no confirmed cases of AFP (acute flaccid paralysis) associated with cVDPV2 in the Gambia.

"In May 2021, with support from the World Health Organisation and other partners, The Gambia initiated environmental surveillance to supplement the traditional (Acute Flaccid Paralysis-AFP) polio surveillance system. Presently, environmental samples are collected from 3 sites. Samples collected from AFP cases and the environment are sent to the regional polio laboratory in Dakar for analysis." Dr. Samateh [the Minister of Health, The Gambia] explained.

"He noted that no AFP sample from The Gambia has tested positive for polio. However, 2 environmental samples collected from sewage sites, 1 from Banjul and the other from Kotu have tested positive for poliovirus type 2.

"'This has created a polio outbreak situation in the country since a single positive poliovirus case is considered an outbreak under the 2005 International Health Regulations, thereby requiring an urgent response to breaking transmission.'

"He added that sequencing results showed that the viruses detected in The Gambia are genetically linked to other viruses detected in Guinea, Senegal, and Nigeria which indicated evidence of importation. He noted that the outbreak is an evidence of poliovirus circulation within the population but does not mean a detection of polio paralysis in the population." (Source: The Point https://thepoint.gm/africa/gambia/headlines/poliovirus-type-2-outbreak-declared-in-gambia)

Sources:
https://thepoint.gm/africa/gambia/headlines/poliovirus-type-2-outbreak-declared-in-gambia
https://www.africanews.com/2021/08/19/gambia-orders-mass-immunization-after-poliovirus-found-in-sewage-water/
https://allafrica.com/stories/202108190264.html

